In <strnlghtCt7xM3.AFx@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:

>In article <ian.774582352@bvsd.k12.co.us>,
>Ian S. Nelson <ian@bvsd.k12.co.us> wrote:

>>
>>>I thought the general consensus of net.lawyers is that WRITING PGP doesn't
>>>violated the RSA patents, only USING it.  Hence, Phil doesn't owe RSA/PKP
>>>anything (except under the doctrine of contributory infringement.)

>Nope. The patent laws provide for _making_ as well as using. Thus writing
>PGP is an infringement.

We've gone through this before.  You're still wrong.  A _computer program_
is not a _device_ which, if "made", can infringe a patent.  _Use_ of the
computer program can infringe.

